2. Data Analysis - Song Characteristics

Valence & Energy

We are also able to ask for some more complex results using the GROUP BY function.

In the example below, we can group our nominated and winning songs by year, then average the valence for each year. 'Valence' is a psychological term; in this case it measures each song's emotional content. 1 equates to a highly positive emotion with zero indicating highly negative. [Source: https://developer.echonest.com]. EchoNest uses a combination of human response and machine learning to classify each song, so there could potentially be a few anomalies.

In [8]:
hyu = pd.read_sql("SELECT year, AVG(valence) AS avValence FROM works w, songs s WHERE w.echo_SONGID=s.echo_SONGID GROUP BY w.year", con=engine)

Right away we can see that in 1971 and again in 1981 the average valence levels were lower than in other years. We can plot these results to see if there are any other distinguishing features:

Putting these into bins shows two clusters in the mid to high 0.4's, then again around the mid-50's, then early 60's. If we look at this again by year and average valence, we can see a slight positive trend over time:

In [10]:
plt.scatter(hyu['year'], hyu['avValence'], facecolor=newcolours[1], s=50)
rcParams['figure.figsize'] = 15, 8

Interestingly, in the 1960's we can see that average valence was clustered around the 0.4-0.6 region. There appears to be a greater spread during the 1970's with more periods of lower average valence seen amongst the nominees. During this time the economy in the US was less successful than during the post-war boom years. The mid-1980's saw the boom during the Regan years - and the average valence has also increased. Since 2000, the average valence can be seen in clusters appearing above 0.45. In the pre-Global Financial Crisis period (2000-2006/7) we can see that average valence was higher than usual, pulling back during and post GFC to lower levels. Although this is a small sample, we could argue that nomination since 2000 could be more likely to occur if your song is happier, rather than sad.

In comparison, the EchoNest have analysed the 5,000 most popular songs every year since 1950, then provided average valence for each year. This can be seen in the scatter plot below where we overlay these averages (blue) with out existing data:

If anything, we can see a "happiness peak" in the EchoNest data from the early to mid-1980's, then a slow decline on average every year with a few peaks here and there. If this overlay with our Grammy nominees data we can see (not unexpectedly given the difference in sample sizes) that the two samples diverge. However, What is noticeable is that post-2000, when valence across the most popular songs has decreased on average, the Grammy nominated songs average valence by year has remained high (and even seen a slight increase).

Paul Lamere, Director of Developer Platform at EchoNest, explained the relationship between energy (arousal) and valence. High energy / high valence equates to positive emotions - astonishment, delight, happiness. Low energy but high valence also equate to positive emotion, but on a more sedate scale (pleased, content, satisfied). On the flipside, high energy but low valence equate to negatively aroused emotions such as alarm, anger and annoyance. Low valence and low energy equate to misery, boredom and tiredness. These are showsn below in Russell's Valence-Arousal space:

In [3]:

Interestingly, it appears that to be nominated it is advantageous to be in the upper right or lower left quadrants. To a lesser extent, the lower right quadrant placement (a sedate kind of happy) could also be a good place to be. There are fewer songs in the upper left quadrant (an agressive kind of unhappy); those that are are clustered towards the central point.

From this, we could potentially infer that you are less likely to win if you are in the "aggressive kind of unhappy" quadrant. We can compare winners to nominees on an individual basis below and see:

The top left quadrant has 39 songs in total - 14 of which were winners. The bottom left quadrant has 87 songs in total, 20 of which were winners. Contrast this with the 110 songs in the high energy/high valence quadrant; only 12 of these won.

The winners in the low valence/low energy quadrant are more likely to have a valence rating between 0 and 0.25. Likewise, the upper right quadrant winners are visible at the margins as opposed to the centre of the quadrant where the losing nominees are.

The two most heavily populated quadrants - upper right and lower left - have a total of 197 of the 285 songs.

This tells us that although nominees are more likely to be high energy/high valence or low energy/low valence, it does not guarantee a win. In fact, songs deemed "sadder" have won more often than happier songs. There could be a number of reasons for this. An aggressively sad song, surrounded by happy peppy songs, may stand out more in the minds of voters. Likewise, happy peppy songs surrounded by similar songs may split the vote, leaving the sad song to win.

Although happier songs have the slight edge in nominations (159/285), sadder songs appear to have the edge when it comes to winning (34/57).

We can now group songs by decade and see if there are any trends. Firstly, we add a new column to our dataframe and apply a function that determines which decade a song fits into (note, as we only have one song from the 1950's this has been grouped in with the 1960's):

In [24]:
evwin.insert(1, 'decade', '')
def func001(dec1):
    if dec1['year'] <= 1969:
        return 1960
    elif 1969 < dec1.year < 1980:
        return 1970
    elif 1979 < dec1.year < 1990:
        return 1980
    elif 1989 < dec1.year < 2000:
        return 1990
    elif 1999 < dec1.year < 2010:
        return 2000
    else:
        return 2010
    
evwin['decade'] = evwin.apply(func001, axis=1)

The first plot shows the Grammy winners during the 1960's (blue) and 1970's (orange). In the 1960's there are some distinct clusters: 1960-61 & 1969 (Mrs. Robinson) sit just inside the more energetic-unhappy quadrant , 1962-64 have low valence/low energy, then 1959 plus the middle of the 1960's is characterised by happier but lower-energy winning songs. The 1970's saw a definite shift towards low happiness/low energy songs, with the exception of Captain & Tenille's peppy "Love Will Keep Us Together". Over both decades, winning songs tended to have energy levels less than 0.5.

The 1980's (purple) saw a rise in winning song energy levels (and a buoyant American economy in the mid-to-late decade), with a cluster appearing in the high energy/high valence quadrant. The exception was Paul Simon's "Graceland", with it's high energy/low valence - a reflection of its upbeat sounding music but lyrics dealing with Simon's thoughts on his marriage break up. The 1990's saw a shift back to the low valence/low energy type of song, with the exception of Sheryl Crow's "All I Wanna Do" in 1995 (valence = 0.92) and Eric Clapton's 1997 hit "Change The World" (0.82 energy).

The 2000's winning songs were centrally clustered, with only one outlier (Santana's "Smooth", energy = 0.92). The 2010-14 songs showed a year on year increase in valence until Sam Smith's 2015 winning song "Stay With Me" (lower right quadrant).

What does this tell us? The trend since the 1980's appears to be away from songs with low energy and low happiness levels. There was a shift back in the 1990's when slower songs like "I Will Always Love You" and "Tears in Heaven" dominated, but the 21st Century saw a shift away. Valence levels had been increasing post 2010 until Sam Smith's win in 2015. Does Smith's win show a new trend emerging or just an outlier?

One of the more controversial subjects in the music industry has been the increase in loudness, particularly since the advent of compact discs in the 1990's. Loudness in this context doesn't just mean the volume music is listened to; the EchoNest summarise it as "by compressing softer and louder sounds within each song into a smaller area – basically, amping up the softest instances to make them closer to the loudest instances – and then cramming that narrower band of loudness right up against the maximum a particular format can take. Although it reduces dynamic range (the distance between the loudest and softest sound you hear on a given recording), the overall effect is to create a perception that the song is louder."

Our chart below compares EchoNest's 5,000 top songs per year since 1950 to our Grammy nominated works:

Until approximately 2000 we can see that nominated songs tended to spend between 1 and 20 weeks in the UK singles chart. Around 2000 we start to see a change in the data, with a larger spread of results (Lady Gaga's "Poker Face" spent 83 consecutive weeks in the charts with Black Eyed Peas' "I Gotta Feeling" in the charts for 75 consecutive weeks).

From 2006 onwards, we see that all but three of the charting nominees spent at least 10 consecutive weeks in the charts (the exceptions being "Not Ready to Make Nice" in 2007, "Lonely Boy" (2013) and "Thinkin Bout You" (also 2013)). There is a definitive upswing in chart longevity; this can be attributed in part to the increase in digital sales (so sales are easier to track) and greater rigour around point of sale data in stores. There have also been studies done which measured liklihood of download if a "top list" was visible when selecting songs. These conclusively showed that rankings did affect downloads as people naturally gravitated to already popular songs. Even when the rankings were flipped - so the truly lowest ranked was noted as being at the top - then this same behaviour persisted with the least popular songs suddenly becoming popular [Source: http://www.theatlantic.com/magazine/archive/2014/12/the-shazam-effect/382237/]. It could also be that a Grammy nomination effectively acts as advertising; in the age of social media and advanced communications technology if sufficient buzz is generated then people may be induced to listen to and then purchase the song.

Language Analysis

We can now turn to the words used in song titles to see if there are any common features. Excepting "Volare", "Desafinado", "Livin' La Vida Loca" and "Viva La Vida" the remainder of our song titles are in English.

Firstly, we pass can import some of the modules from nltk, a language processor, then pass our variable "work" and its contents to a set called results. From there, we can tokenize, strip out the punctation and then format this data as nltk text.

We can then use nltk's Frequency Distribution to assess the frequency distribution of the words within our song titles:

In [63]:

from nltk.tokenize import RegexpTokenizer

A quick assessment provides a summary of some of the analysis previously documented in this report. There are the expected positive correlations - e.g. the higher the danceability rating the higher the valence, which is unsurprising given dancing to a sad song is perhaps less enjoyable than a happy one.

There is an interesting negative correlation between number of characters in a song title and the energy rating of the song (-0.18).

The high position / weeks in chart correlation figures need to be interpreted with care. Essentially, the lower the highest ever chart position (e.g. making number 1), the more likely the song is to have stayed in the charts for more than 5-6 weeks whereas a low chart position makes the song more likely to exit earlier. In summary, the following have been observed:

    1. Losing nominees - there is a stronger positive correlation between song energy and year of nomination (0.51) than can be seen with winning songs (0.34).

    2. Losing songs have a positive correlation between the highest chart position attained and the number of characters in the song title (0.053), whereas winning songs have a negative correlation (-0.1).

    3. The number of characters in a winning song's title is negatively correlated with the year of win (-0.34). For losing songs this is -0.18.

    4. There appears to be a strong correlation between valence and energy amongst our nominees, with the highest number of nominees being in the high valence/high energy quadrant, followed closely by the low energy/low valence quadrant. However, winners proportionately less likely to come from the high-valence / high-energy quadrant.

    5. Song energy tended to increase, peaking in the 1980's, and has now pulled back from those highs. However the central peak of our nominees' energy is less than that of the wider song market.

    6. Valence has increased over the years and has generally been higher than the wider market, especially post-2000.

    7. Nominated songs tend to be longer in length than the perceived industry "gold standard" of approximately 3 minutes. Song length across nominees appears to have typically declined since the 2000's.

    8. Analysis of our song titles shows that pronouns are common, as are common words that are easy to pronounce and the use of shorter (rather than longer) words. Mentioning love or one of its variants (including "heart") could potentially help. Positive words were utilised more often than negative (e.g. beautiful vs lonesome).

    9. Perhaps the most significant previously undiscovered correlation relates to that between song energy and the number of characters in a song title. When all nominees are considered as a pool we can see that this is -0.18. However, when we split the losers and winners out we can see that there are significant differences between the two groups (-0.11 losers; -0.48 winners). This could potentially be because shorter song titles get to the point - inferring energy? Compare this to the low-energy non-nominated "You be the anchor that keeps my feet on the ground, I'll be the wings that keeps your heart in the clouds" by Mayday Parade.
